LSCs are typically made of inexpensive materials, such as plastics containing fluorescent dyes or glass covered with a luminescent coatings [43]. The incoming solar irradiation is absorbed by the luminophores and a significant fraction is re-emitted inside the material. The emitted radiation is guided by total internal reflection towards the edge(s) of the material. According to Snell’s law, when light travels from a high refractive index media to a lower refractive index, a critical angle can be determined (α=sin-1n-1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
